    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "261a7cf0_e7582f2d",
        "filename": "src/gpu/gl/GrGLExtensions.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 142,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-14T19:32:11Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "They\u0027ve removed an item from an already-sorted list using removeShuffle (because SkTArray doesn\u0027t allow erasing from the middle). Almost-perfectly-ordered data is a pathologically bad case for QSort and really efficient for insertion sort. But the \"best\" fix would be for SkTArray to support a proper `erase` method and then no sort would be needed at all.\n\n(In practice I doubt it matters either way since this is probably far off the hot path)",
      "parentUuid": "d91cbc6e_d476b15a",
      "revId": "e6d01aaa81440b832da1a610fb5e68ea2aec70dd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e954b7e3_4806c569",
        "filename": "src/gpu/gl/GrGLExtensions.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 142,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-14T19:43:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "sg.  What I was trying to get at here is that SkTQSort() is not a quicksort, and already chooses among various approaches depending on the data.  It seems like an unusual place to bypass those smarts.  But I wouldn\u0027t change anything with this CL.",
      "parentUuid": "261a7cf0_e7582f2d",
      "revId": "e6d01aaa81440b832da1a610fb5e68ea2aec70dd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "840a2628_b45c0e40",
        "filename": "src/gpu/gl/GrGLExtensions.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 142,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-14T20:04:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "SkTQSort doesn\u0027t really do anything clever based on the contents of the data, it\u0027s just switching between heap/insertion/quicksort approaches the way all introsorts do based on predefined limits. I wouldn\u0027t have called that \"choosing an approach\" as it\u0027s super naive about it--insertion sort below a certain size threshold, heapsort when we blow our depth limit, quicksort the rest of the time. That\u0027s just what introsorts do :) \n\nIt\u0027s not a big deal, and you\u0027re right to question this because it really shouldn\u0027t be sorting at all; it just needs to erase one object from the middle of a sorted list, and insertion sort happens to do the right thing. It\u0027s goofy. \n\n(If you think it\u0027s worthwhile, we could add an erase(index) method to SkTArray and remove the sort here entirely, but my gut feeling is that this is gilding the lily and that you wouldn\u0027t ask for this change.)",
      "parentUuid": "e954b7e3_4806c569",
      "revId": "e6d01aaa81440b832da1a610fb5e68ea2aec70dd",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d5955f34_067f034f",
        "filename": "src/gpu/gl/GrGLExtensions.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 142,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-07-14T20:13:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Oh ok, this insertion sort runs in O(N) time, of course.  I guess I\u0027d have expected std::move() (this one, https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/algorithm/move)?  That said, I don\u0027t see any reason not to add erase() to SkTArray.  It\u0027s weird that it\u0027s missing.\n\nIf we\u0027re gilding anything here, I\u0027d hesitate to call it a lily.",
      "parentUuid": "840a2628_b45c0e40",
      "revId": "e6d01aaa81440b832da1a610fb5e68ea2aec70dd",
